english:
  title: On the Character Mengyi
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the year of Wushen under the Zhizheng reign, I took office as Director of the National Academy, and the number of students was quite abundant. We divided them to study the Five Classics, and those studying the Book of Documents numbered more than eighty. Among them was Liu Jing, whose bearing stood out from the crowd. After receiving his assignments, he would sit upright and read without ceasing. Upon the eight characters "Reverence for Heaven's mandate—only timeliness, only the crucial moment," he would reflect with composure, turning them over again and again. His voice would draw out long, sometimes high, sometimes low. His fellow students would point and laugh, yet Liu Jing paid no mind—thus one could discern the singularity of his heart. In time, all in the academy came to respect him.

    In the year of Xinhai, I was entrusted with administering the civil service examination. Liu Jing passed through mastery of poetic meaning—one could say he had penetrated both the Book of Poetry and Book of Documents. He was appointed to an academic post, and through his labors was promoted to Counselor. The various instructors of the academy petitioned the court, and Liu Jing was given the concurrent post of Exhorting Scholar. Now five years have passed, yet he remains unhonored by further advancement. And yet he dwells in peace, harboring no outward ambitions—surely such tranquility of heart must have reached somewhere profound.

    Now he has asked me to explain his personal name. He said: "Fortunate that friends do not disdain me, I have taken the name Mengyi. I hope to receive your instruction."

    I replied: "In the Canon of Yao, reverence opens the discourse; in the ode to King Wen, respect is proclaimed. Is this not what you have always admired? 'Light spreads to the four quarters'—this flows from reverence; 'the sun's virtue reaches distant lands'—this emanates from respect. When Yao consulted the Four Peaks or stood in temple and court, dwelling in peace yet striving earnestly, the people revered him though he moved not, trusted him though he spoke not. His radiant dignity endures—a thousand years hence, we regard it as of yesterday. Ah, what sublime virtue!

    Yet scholars of today say: 'Yao and Shun, King Wen—these were sages born with perfect knowledge. How dare we aspire?' No wonder the Way declines daily and human hearts grow ever shallower without end.

    But Heaven and Earth are the parents of all things. Whether sage or worthy, foolish or base, all are siblings. Does a parent show favoritism among children? Humans are born; only desire leads them astray. It was then that Heaven, in benevolence, appointed the most excellent to be teachers and rulers, restoring their original goodness. In that age, 'ten thousand realms harmonized' and 'all people flourished'—these were no empty words. The people's righteous conduct and the principles of things were unified within and without, pervading both the subtle and the coarse. Heaven moves freely, and in not a single thing is there absence of benevolence. This spreads through words and deeds, manifests in the four limbs, flowing forth crystalline and abundant. The three hundred rites and three thousand dignities—their generousness and greatness—do they await a particular person to unfold?

    Therefore it is said: 'In every household, virtue may be honored.' Yet to go far, begin near; to climb high, start low. To sweep the courtyard is the pattern for people; at the cock's crow, to rise and labor earnestly—is this not to 'set straight your robes and regard what is noble'? 'When countenance and tone draw near to sincerity, baseness recedes'—these are the words of Zengzi. Zengzi transmitted the Way of Confucius down to this very day. If Mengyi embodies this, then at last he may reverence Heaven's mandate, and at last he may tread upon that vast and generous realm of ritual propriety and dignified bearing.
  footnotes:
    - The eight characters "敕天之命惟時惺幾" (reverence for Heaven's mandate—only timeliness, only the crucial moment) are from the Book of Documents and represent a key passage that Liu Jing studied with particular devotion.
    - 'The Five Classics (五經) refer to the foundational texts of Confucian learning: the Book of Poetry, Book of History/Documents, Book of Rites, Book of Changes, and Spring and Autumn Annals.'
    - Lee Saek employs references to Yao and Shun as exemplary sage-rulers whose virtue operated through presence rather than force, establishing a model for cultivating inner character.
    - The "three hundred rites and three thousand dignities" is a traditional reference to the comprehensive nature of ritual propriety and virtuous bearing in Confucian practice.
